# Summary

For simplicity, we choose to work with a system of first order linear equations that satisfy the constraints to ensure 
[existence and uniqueness](system_of_first_order_linear_equations#existence-and-uniqueness). In particular, 
if each of the functions $g_1(t), \ldots, g_n(t)$ is zero for all $t$ in the interval $I$, then we say the system is 
**homogeneous**. A system of homogeneous equations can be solved very similarly to just a single homogeneous equation,
and solutions/theorems parallel the single equation theory. In particular, we rewrite the system as
$$ \pmb{x}' = \pmb{P}(t), $$ and note that nonhomogeneous solutions follow after solving the corresponding homogeneous
equations. 

</section>

