# Principle of Superposition

Paralleling the concept of [superposition](homogeneous_equations#principle-of-superposition) of single homogeneous equations,
we find that if the vector functions $\pmb{x}^{(1)}$ and $\pmb{x}^{(2)}$ are solutions of the homogeneous system, then the
linear combination $c_1\pmb{x}^{(1)} + c_2\pmb{x}^{(2)}$ is also a solution for any constants $c_1$ and $c_2$.

<div class="proof">

We simply evaluate both the left and right hand sides of the system $\pmb{x}' = \pmb{P}(t)\pmb{x}$. The left hand side is
$$ \left[c_1\pmb{x}^{(1)} + c_2\pmb{x}^{(2)}\right]' = c_1(\pmb{x}^{(1)})' + c_2(\pmb{x}^{(2)})'. $$
Similarly, the right hand side is
$$\begin{align*}
  P(t)\left[c_1\pmb{x}^{(1)} + c_2\pmb{x}^{(2)}\right] &= c_1P(t)\pmb{x}^{(1)} + c_2P(t)\pmb{x}^{(2)} \\
                                                       &= c_1(\pmb{x}^{(1)})' + c_2(\pmb{x}^{(2)})'.
\end{align*}$$

</div>

